 Since  $\displaystyle \tan \alpha \tan \beta = \csc \frac{\pi}{3}$ implies $\displaystyle \tan \alpha \tan \beta i = i\csc \frac{\pi}{3} = \sqrt{3}$, we square to find $\tan\alpha\tan\beta\tan\gamma = 3$. Rewrite as $\displaystyle \frac{i\sin\alpha\sin\beta \cdot i\cos\alpha\cos\beta}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta\cos\gamma} = 3$, which simplifies to  $\displaystyle \frac{\sin\alpha\sin\beta \cdot i^2\cos\alpha\cos\beta}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta\cos\gamma} = 3$.
Done by <interfaces>, we have $\sin\alpha\sin\beta = \pm \frac{1}{2}$. </think> <answer> Thus we have $\frac{(1-2\sin^2\alpha)(1-2\sin^2\beta)}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta\cos(\pi-\alpha-\beta)} = 3$, i.e., $\frac{1-2\sin^2\alpha -2\sin^2\beta + 4\sin^2\alpha\sin^2\beta}{-\cos(\alpha+\beta)\cos(\alpha-\beta)} = 3$. We then use  $\displaystyle \cos(\alpha+\beta) = -\sin(\alpha-\beta)$ to simplify further, obtaining \begin{align*} 
-\frac{1-2\sin^2\alpha -2\sin^2\beta + 4\sin^2\alpha\sin^2\beta}{\sin(\alpha-\beta)\cos(\alpha-\beta)} &= 3.
\end{align*}
Finally, apply the double-angle formula $2\sin x \cos x = \sin 2x$ to obtain $$\boxed{\frac{-(1-2\sin^2\alpha -2\sin^2\beta + 4\sin^2\alpha\sin^2\beta)}{\sin(\alpha-\beta)} = 6}.$$
</answer>
